AGI - Praying and the Eucharist are "a very powerful therapy of which the Pope does not deprive himself": it has emphasized the chaplain of the Gemelli, the chaplain Nunzio Currao, during the daily prayer for the Pontiff, admitted from 14 days in the Roman polyclinic for a pneumonia.
&nbsp;
"Every day the medical report says that the Pope rested well, prayed and received the Eucharist," said the chaplain, "according to you, there is a need for a medical flyer to say these things?" The message is that "praying, being in intimacy with the Lord, receiving the medicine of immortality, the bread of the pilgrims" are "a very powerful therapy of which the Pope does not deprive himself" and that "we must never deprive ourselves of the Eucharist".
&nbsp;
"Pope Francis is living in the first person the mystery of human fragility, his moments of suffering - he adds the priest - but even before his shelter he has assumed the mission, the love for the Church and the passion for the Gospel, he has also submitted it to his health. We have seen fatigue I think that whoever would have said to him, Holy Father, rests a little more, does not bother." "We gather in prayer so that the Lord Jesus may sustain him, give him health, give him strength so that he can still proclaim to the world the joy and tenderness of the Gospel," he concludes.
&nbsp;
"Papa Francesco teaches us simplicity, simplicity. Even the same things he lives with that sobriety he always wanted when he came here in Polyclinic. Always enter confidentially, does not want to bother, simplicity. That's nice. Let us return, that there really is this return to this simplicity, but at the same time living the Gospel in fullness". This is said in the homily during the Mass in the chapel St. John Paul II of the Gemelli the chaplain Fr Nunzio Currao, dedicating a thought to Pope Francis admitted for 14 days on the tenth floor of the polyclinic. During the celebration in the Greek hat to the inverosimile, the priest recalled three eminent figures of the Gemini: the cardiovascular surgeon Gegrorio China, who died today, the primary of radiotherapy Numa Cellini died in early February ago and above all the luminaire of gynecological oncology, Giovanni Exchangea ('Giovannino' as he called it Currao of which he was very friend), died after a short illness a week ago at 65 years.
&nbsp;
Speaking of Pope Francis, the chaplain of the Gemelli then wanted to give the faithful a personal memory: "When he was elected Pope, on March 13, 2013, remember that in the evening when he fell into the central lodge he asked for prayer, the blessing of the people and then said: tomorrow I want to go to pray to Our Lady to Santa Maria Maggiore, 'Salus Populi Romani' - says Fr Currao in his homily - was accompanied by Cardinal Agostino Vallini who was the vicar of Rome and that the Pope wanted to his side when he fell into the central lodge of St. Peter, which had not come the other times, but he wanted his vicar to be there because the Pope strongly emphasizes his being Bishop of Rome. When in a meeting at the Vicariate we asked Cardinal Vallini what his sensations were - he continued - he said that the Pope was strongly impressed by all the people who were fighting around the car, around him. And the Pope asked the Cardinal: What do they want? How are all these people?' Cardinal Vallini replied: Holy Father, I'm here for you. To which the Pope told him: 'Don't worry, that the 'francescanite acuta' will end soon.' But why? Not because you no longer want to the Pope, but because he is so, bread to bread and wine to wine. He says things as they are. He is slowly bringing us back to evangelical radicalism," he adds.&nbsp;

