AGI -&nbsp; A ray of petrified light. That's what the obelisk is: the divine that illuminates man on earth.> And Rome barks, of monoliths counts thirteen, some brought from Egypt and others made in the West to their imitation. The first to want them on the imperial soil was the great Octavian Augustus. The mighty granite stems had fascinated him and wished that those representations of greatness also dwelt in the cradle city of his kingdom.
Originally the obelisks were born as an image of the “gran capo” of the Egyptian pantheon >: the god Amon, later fussed with Ra and finally became Amon-Ra, first version of monotheism. But those granite grinders are something more and can also be interpreted according to another symbolism. According to a Christian reading, obelisks are divine light on men. Lighting comes from Heaven, focuses on the tip of the monument and then wanders on men through the small pyramid on the top (pyramidion, removed from some obelisks).
From 31 BC Augustus began the move of works. He had the giants in the present squares of the People and Montecitorio. Then, the other sculptures put up by his successors were added: at Villa Celimontana, in the squares of the Quirinale, of the Esquilino, in Piazza Navona, of the Round, of the Cinquecento, in Trinità dei Monti, > to the Pantheon and the Bennian Elephant in Piazza della Minerva>. Finally, the two oldest obelisks.
For a small waste of time the primacy goes to the colossus in Piazza San Giovanni in Laterano (from the 15th century BC, 32 meters high and without base). Then follow what is in front of St. Peter's Square. The obelisks before the basilicas were expressly desired by the pontiff who established the new rule: who had stopped there before praying would have earned an indulgence.
